4.1 Cochise County Local Emergency Planning Committee (CcLEPC) The CCLEPC, in coordination with the CCEM, private facilities, fire departments/districts, and other federal, state, and local entities: O Identifies and analyze the risks of hazardous materials being manufactured, stored, used, or transported in the county; Establishes clear procedures for emergency notification, public warning, evacuation, and sheltering for hazardous material incidents; Assists the public with information requests for hazardous materials being manufactured, stored, used, or transported in the county; Identifies community lifelines and underserved community vulnerabilities to hazardous materials. releases; O Makes recommendations to the Cochise County Development Services on the development of hazardous material facilities/sites in vulnerable areas; and Coordinates hazardous materials training and exercise programs for responders. 4.2 Private Sector Fixed Facilities Initial actions for private facilities include but are not limited to:. Control releases on-site to the extent possible;

4.3 Private Sector Transportation Companies Train their personnel on hazardous materials incidents and emergency communications consistent with established standards; Comply with all applicable DOT and other applicable regulations regarding the transportation of hazardous materials or waste; Notify the NRC when an RQ is released from one of their units; and. Coordinate with the IC/uc and the authority having jurisdiction for response and cleanup activities. 4.4 Fire Districts/Departments Follow established sops/sOGs for training, exercising, and responding to hazardous materials incidents; Receive and maintain reports and Safety Data Sheets (SDs) from hazardous materials facilities (through AZsERC's Tier II database) and use them in developing SOPs/SOGs and pre-plans for hazardous material emergencies; Report all hazardous materials spills to AzDEQ through their electronic spill reporting form; Familiarize their personnel on site-specific facility emergency response plans from facilities required to submit under EPCRA and ARS Title 49, Chapter 1;. Identify community lifelines and underserved community vulnerabilities to hazardous materials releases;

4.5 Incorporated Jurisdictions Support their jurisdictional fire authority in their duties; Cooperate with CCEM and CCLEPC on hazardous materials incident planning, training, exercising, and response and recovery activities; and. Train their personnel, such as law enforcement or roadway personnel, on hazardous materials incidents consistent with established standards.. 4.6 County of Cochise. Train their personnel, such as law enforcement or roadway personnel, on hazardous materials incidents consistent with established standards..
